
[1]distaste

   DISTASTE, n. [dis and taste.]

   1. Aversion of the taste; dislike of food or drink; disrelish; disgust,
   or a slight degree of it. Distaste for a particular kind of food may be
   constitutional, or the effect of a diseased stomach.

   2. Dislike; uneasiness.

   Prosperity is not without many fears and distastes, and adversity is
   not without comfort and hopes.

   3. Dislike; displeasure; alienation of affection.

                               DISTASTE, v.t.

   1. To disrelish; to dislike; to lothe; as, to distaste drugs or
   poisons.

   2. To offend; to disgust.

   He thought it no policy to distaste the English or Irish, but sought to
   please them.

   3. To vex; to displease; to sour.

                  [The two latter significations are rare.]
